Women vs - The mission was to create a stereo type that would last through the ages. One that exists even today with help from people like Lee Daniels & Danny Strong During the era of the Jim Crow laws, it was a crime for Blacks to argue with White people, Black women were given a leeway to which was not only supposed to represent their acceptance into White families as “mammies? This stereotype portrays Black women as not only offering help to the White families but it also showcases Black women with anger and masculinity. Many movie producers today keep this stereotype alive in order to influence younger woman that this is how are supposed to act. Tyler Perry for example: He showcases himself as a Black woman, Madea. Madea is portrayed as a big, black, strong, hostile and sometimes illogical woman who has the tendency to overreact with force and violence when she has been wronged or wants to defend herself. She is also portrayed as extremely nurturing and cares a lot about the well-being of children and teenagers but never hesitant to “lash out?on them anytime they showed signs of disrespect. She involves herself in the situations of others, giving them advice and offering self-defense tips or methods of vengeance when needed. Moreover, her hospitality is overridden by her comical aggressiveness demonstrated more to the audience which adds to the false depiction of Black women. On the other hand, Lee Daniels and Danny Strong’s television show, Empire, is another example of the stereotype of the trope of angry Black woman. In fact, one of the main characters, Cookie Lyon is an embodiment of the stereotype Black women face in the film. This show represents a tough motherly figure who was born and raised in the “hood?around drug dealers and gangs. She served 17 years in prison, away from her children and did not get to watch them grow up. She along with her husband, Lucious Lyons, were fortunate enough to form a company known as Empire, which took them from rags to riches. The elegance can be seen through what she wears with knee-high boots, fashionable fur coats, long color-coded nails, but her short temper and violent tendencies tend to overshadow her good. Black women continue to be affected by this stereotype, in the sense that people who have been conditioned to view African American women as angry Black women, respond to Black women’s emotions with fear. With this trope as one of the biggest topics and issues in Black film, and the lack of diversity of Black women in film which can leave an impression on the audience that Black women are all always angry. We must set aside these stereotypes and Black Women today need to grab hold instead of the qualities that our Father in heaven declares are righteous. No matter what situation we find ourselves in, if its even remotely stressful in any way, or possibly could be stressful, anxiety will take that and run with it. We have to be constantly on our game to either head off anxiety before it starts or minimize its effect on us once it begins to try to assert it’s power. One of the things that anxiety is so good at it, is being versatile. By constantly changing its tactics on the fly, we have to stay vigilant on our own behalf and fight this battle against a relentless foe. Make no mistake though, friends, anxiety is not unbeatable! If you remember back to a previous trick we talked about in this series, anxiety wants us to think that every situation is going to turn out awful, and be the worst thing we have ever experienced. Which brings us to the next trick, an off shoot of that tactic is that anxiety also wants us to live in fear. Living in fear is no way to live if we want to have a peaceful, happy, life full of contentment. Anxiety loves nothing more than to not allow that to happen, and it will try to use fear to its advantage. That’s one thing about anxiety, it pulls no punches and leaves no stone unturned; no tactic is off the table. Fear in itself is not a bad thing, we are all born with this healthy instinct. so, we did it. i just came back to this blog (after suffering a case of finding myself and loving it) in order to get my thoughts back to that creative space outside of my mind. you know how it goes when life distracts you from living? yeah. anyway, i forgot that i really liked the format i chose. it surprised me that i had dropped writing on this platform, yet it confirmed how lost inside the lemons of life i’d gotten?especially when i saw the first one?and then the fourth (or whatever number of re-blogs after). i. was. depressed. af. i wanted love so badly. i risked my life for it. literally in all ways. times like these bring me closer to myself, fortunately. because once i finally realized the person i am is exactly the person i thought i was, i made lemonade out of those lemons. (and of course that’s such a cheesy cliche, but it fits, so whatever.) ? darius and i got married on october 18, 2016 and it was one of the happiest days of my life. i’d finally gotten what my entire life had been governed by: a partner. a forever thing. s e c u r i t y. i used to joke with him (in whatever serious capacity a joke could be taken) about not wanting to be bothered on our wedding day. it was to be a day that was free from my anxious mind running amok - no questions, no wondering, no assumptions of bad intent. and that’s exactly what he gave me. even though i developed a serious migraine (which ended up being the start of a biyearly sinus infection), darius gave me a dream day. he took into account everything and handled it before it had a chance to bother me. nothing seemed like it could bother us that day. and after hiccup after hiccup after hiccup after hiccup after hiccup, we’ve successfully gotten right back to that bliss? (we’ll get into the hiccups later)

Considering where our city is today I did not expect to be inspired the way I was when by some quirk of fate I got a chance to visit Raj Bhavin, the Governor’s estate at Walkeshwar earlier this week. We truly felt like guests as we were escorted around the estate by the warm and courteous Raj Bhavan team. The estate itself is sprawled over 46 acres and by their records has over 3000 different trees. There were several peacocks and many varieties of birds. And everything is immaculately maintained. As we sat at the sunrise point and experienced the sunrise we were mesmerised by the stunning scene that unfolded. That entire moment and the estate truly showed us what Mumbai was like in the past and honestly what it’s potential is. This was that moment of inspiration. We as Mumbaikars can expect to get our city back and drive the powers that be to revive and recreate the city the way it was. G & I chose to walk around and take in the green experience. This was truly invigorating despite the summer heat. It is very special to be ensconced in greenery within the city. This little forest in the heart of the city lifted our spirits. Getting up at 4.30, showering and reaching the Raj Bhavan gate 5.45 am was quite a challenge. But in hindsight I am really glad that we did it. The experience was truly surreal and inspiring. (at Raj Bhavan (Mumbai))

Кокосовое масло. 🌴🌴🌴🌴🌴🌴 Одно из самых популярных сегодня ?масло кокоса. Его привозят из Таиланда, Индонезии и других жарких стран. Применяют внутренне и наружно, делают маски для волос и используют вместо крема, приписывая этой субстанции самые невероятные свойства. Адепты кокосового масла уверяют, что оно разглаживает морщины, придает коже упругость, восстанавливает поврежденные волосы, способствует похудению и т.д. Давайте разберемся, где правда, а где ?вымысел. Кокосовое масло состоит из ненасыщенных жирных кислот, которые сходны с липидами нашей кожи. Именно поэтому оно идеально восстанавливает гидролипидную пленку ?защитный барьер кожи, попутно делая ее мягкой, шелковистой и гладкой. Действие масла чисто механическое и поверхностное. Оно не проникает в клетки, не может повлиять на их работу и каким-либо образом остановить старение. Кокосовое масло, как и все растительные масла, ?это нелетучее органическое вещество. Его способность «удерживать влагу» (хотя на самом деле оно ее не удерживает, а отталкивает) объясняется гидрофобными свойствами. Поэтому правильнее всего наносить масло на влажную кожу после душа, а затем промакивать полотенцем. Так субстанция как бы запечатает влагу, не давая ей испариться. Если у вас очень сухая шелушащаяся кожа, можно дважды в неделю делать маски для тела с применением кокосового масла. Для этого после душа нужно сначала нанести увлажняющий крем с гиалуроновой кислотой (она проникает внутрь клеток, куда никакое масло не доберется), сверху щедрым слоем нанести кокосовое масло и для усиления эффекта обернуть пленкой. Такие маски отлично подходят для заживления трещинок на пятках, коленях, локтях и других огрубевших участках тела. (at Planet Earth)

About a month ago, I’m waiting for a medical test when the nurse walks out and starts grinning from ear to ear as she says hello to a woman in the room. They exchange greetings, and then the nurse looks down at the piece of paper in her hand and calls out the next victim’s, I mean patient’s name, which is mine. I look over my shoulder as I walk through the door with her and say, “See you soon, Mom.? The nurse suddenly realizes the woman she’d been so happy to see is with me. “That’s your Mom?!??she exclaims, eyes wide. I grin. “Yep.? She smiles again. “Oh, she’s SO beautiful.? I chuckle. “Yeah,?I nod. The nurse’s brow weaves together. “Oh, you’re beautiful, too,?she adds quickly. I laugh as she begins telling me why she thinks my mom is so special and beautiful, and quickly I figure out that though she may have only met my mom a handful of times over the years, she knows what most people know…Mom is beautiful inside and out, and that my friends, really is something. Here’s a little birthday card I wrote for the mothership. If you see Jacquelyn, give her a hug? She prays without end She’s always a friend, She falls, she gets up She tries again She explores, she sees, She hikes, she believes She gardens, she listens She inspires, she sings She’s sugar and spice, She laughs till she cries She gives everything, She dares you to dream True beauty, the real deal Authentic, naturally, She’s a helper, she’s a fighter She’s there for you and me. HAPPY BIRTHDAY, MOM! I love you. Love your favorite pain, (AKA the middle child), Sarah xoxoxo

Today marks my 1 year,this picture is all I have to show for it, it the only one I got to take. I remember being told ?don’t get your hopes up.? but I noticed a bump, that gave me hope. A few days later I was sitting lounging on the couch I tried to ignore the pain that felt like an oncoming endo attack. I did my best to sing to you and read you Dr suess and let myself think it was a normal pregnancy thing. The pain started to get worse and I could feel the blood running down my legs and I still told myself ?Kenzie ignore it everything is fine you’ve felt worse pain?But then there i was doubled over on the floor screaming for someone to save me I remember my dad telling me it’d be ok and his hands brushing through my hair, then eventually being told they had to do an emergency removal and I had been given 2 pints of blood. I just felt empty, you were the one thing that had given me hope I was so convinced that I was going to show a small portion of the world that good amazing things can come from evil people and that I’d get to show you how damn lucky and thankful I was to be your mom. But then I just get sent home with nothing, but pain, heartbreak, smashed dreams and goals I’d never get to achieve. I remember not understanding why (and I still don’t) I left an abusive relationship for you and I recorded myself reading Dr suess because my goal was go train you to be able to stop crying when being completely lost on what to do so I figured and had hoped that by recording my voice reading and playing it for you while in the womb,that when you came into this world and just needed to know it’s ok reading would do the trick. The last few months I have often wondered would I be changing you, feeding you, watching you sleep, how much youd of grown and the milestones you’d of been making, but I’m just missing you and sad that I never got the chance to hold you or name you and be the mom you deserved.
